# Documentation Rules

When making meaningful architectural or structural changes:
- update README if setup changes
- update docs if workflow changes
- document new modules, new environment variables, new queue jobs, new schema assumptions

Prefer short, useful documentation over long vague documentation.

---

# Security Rules

Never:
- hardcode secrets
- commit API keys
- expose internal-only endpoints casually
- skip auth/authorization considerations on filing or document endpoints

Always consider:
- sensitive tax data handling
- file upload safety
- permission boundaries
- audit logs for critical state changes

Security boundaries:
- frontend never stores secrets
- backend enforces authorization
- tax engine only receives the data it needs
- logs must avoid leaking sensitive values where possible

---

# Performance Rules

Prefer:
- paginated data views
- selective data fetching
- memoization only where justified
- efficient table rendering for large datasets
- background jobs for slow tasks

Avoid:
- fetching everything by default
- over-rendering large form trees
- putting heavy calculations in the browser if they belong in Rust/backend
